Level Difficulty: Medium - High
Commands Used: nmap,openssl,chmod,ssh,cat
              nmap -> network scanner, checks a range of ports on a host to see which ones are open and what service is running
              openssl -> s_client lets it connect to a port like a TLS client, same as we used last level
              chmod -> changes file permissions
              ssh -> logs into a remote machine, -i lets us point to a specific private key
              cat -> reads and prints file content
Steps: nmap -p 31000-32000 -sV localhost [scans the given port range and shows which ports are open, -sV also tries to guess what service/version is running on each so we know which ones are worth checking]
       openssl s_client -connect localhost:PORT [connects to each open port one by one using TLS, since we already learned last level that some of these services expect an encrypted connection rather than plain nc]
       [one of the ports handed back an RSA private key directly in the response instead of asking for a password]
       <copied the private key block into a file in our tmp working dir> use mktemp -d or mkdir dir_name [saved everything between -----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY----- and -----END RSA PRIVATE KEY----- exactly as printed]
       chmod 600 <keyfile> [ssh refuses to use a key with loose permissions, 600 = only the owner can read/write it]
       ssh -i <keyfile> bandit17@localhost -p 2220 [logs in as bandit17 using the key we just found]
       cat /etc/bandit_pass/bandit17 [now that we ARE bandit17, read the password file directly]
